action.text: Rica Rosario Valencia assigned to Joel Maligalig

full_threads.body:
Hi Wolf IQ,

We are discontinuing support for the obsolete PHP version 7.4. It is critical that you update your sites to PHP 8 as soon as possible!

On January 24, 2023, we will begin updating sites still using PHP 7.4 to PHP 8.0.

If you take no action, we will update your sites to PHP 8.0. The updates will take place over several weeks, but all PHP 7.4 sites are subject to being updated anytime after January 24.

We don't recommend waiting for us to update your sites. Some breaking changes between PHP 7.4 and 8.0 may affect your sites, so we urge you to switch your sites to PHP 8.0 before the automatic changes begin on January 24, 2023.

How to upgrade to the latest version of PHP

Upgrading PHP versions in MyKinsta is as easy as selecting a new version from a dropdown menu. Our safe PHP upgrades guide provides step-by-step instructions.

The best way to ensure that going from PHP 7.4 to 8.0 will not break any of your site functions is to test the changes in a staging environment, then update your live site when you're satisfied that your site is working correctly with the new PHP version.

What to look for when testing your site with PHP 8

Unless you're running an older version of WordPress, PHP version incompatibilities are most likely to be found in themes or plugins rather than WordPress itself.

  • If you are running an old version of WordPress, we recommend updating it before testing or updating PHP.
  • Update your theme and plugins to the latest versions before testing or updating PHP.

If your site breaks when using PHP 8.0 in staging, troubleshoot by disabling one plugin at a time. If you disable a particular plugin and your site starts working again, you've found what you need to address. If plugins are not the problem, try disabling your theme.

If a theme or plugin version is not compatible with PHP 8, contact the developer to see if they have a timeline for compatibility. If not, look for another plugin or theme to replace it.

If you need a developer to assist with testing, we have a list of partners who may be able to help.

Unsupported versions of PHP are a security risk

There are no fixes for security vulnerabilities that arise in unsupported PHP versions, which is why Kinsta removes the option to use unsupported versions. More recent versions of PHP are not only safer, but they're also often faster than the versions they replace.

If you want to read about some of the benefits and changes, check out our article, What's New in PHP 8.

We're here to help

Everyone at Kinsta is dedicated to providing you with the fastest, safest, and most secure website hosting environment anywhere. Technology updates can be inconvenient and disruptive; we know that. But occasional updates are necessary to maintain the safety and performance you've come to expect.

We're here for you if you have questions about the PHP version changes. Feel free to connect with us in MyKinsta.
The Kinsta Team
